	<td class="alt1">
	
		
			<!-- icon and title -->
			<div class="smallfont">
				<img class="inlineimg" src="images/icons/icon1.gif" alt="Default" border="0" />
				<strong>Gamers Rights</strong>
			</div>
			<hr size="1" style="color:#000000" />
			<!-- / icon and title -->
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>Some of you may have read <a href="http://www.avault.com/articles/getarticle.asp?name=mmogsell" target="_blank">this</a> editorial regarding Blacksnow's case against Mythic entertainment. After reading the article I felt like I had to say something.<br />
<br />
First off, I'm not a huge fan of EB players but I also don't think that people should be prohibited from buying or selling characters/items online. The problem I see with allowing the selling of in-game items is the possibility of commercial guilds developing. My fear is that individual players would find themselves competing with 'employees' for in game content.<br />
<br />
I honestly can't say how much this might effect the balance of the game world but I believe it would significant impact on the middle to high level gamer. Don't get me wrong, I don't think any development company should have the right to forbid me to do whatever I want with my character or items. If I did sell my character (which I wouldn't), the person who bought it would still have to pay the monthly fee to play.<br />
<br />
Development companies wouldn't lose money if they allowed the buying and selling of content for real dollars, but I do fear that the legitimate player would be effected.<br />
<br />
If I ran a development company, I would not for bide real world transactions of characters and items, but I would feel the need to limit commercial opportunities.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		<!-- sig -->
			<div>
				__________________<br />
				~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br />
<b>Soldara Widowmaker</b><br><br />
Ayonae Ro<br>
